description:
Pacific Newt (alive & injured)

Saturday: I found this little guy on the side of the road. It's eyes were open and it looked alive, so I picked it up and put it in the grass. Notice the tail - it's split. I continued the roadkill survey and returned about 15 minutes later - it hadn't moved. I'm not sure it will survive.

2019-03-06 (Wed): I found this little guy dead about 3 inches from where I left him on Saturday.

This will be a good subject for the decomposition rate study since it's not on the road now and so it won't be run over by numerous cars.

*** Decomposition Rate Study *** 
These observations show the decomposition of a newt over time. This will give us a sense of how fast the bodies decompose so that duplicate entries aren't added to the main project and the total count is more accurate.

description:
CAP: 46 - 55 mm dia. White w/ brn raised squamules.  Marshmallow shape on immature specimens. 
FLESH: firm, white, slowly staining bright yellow under KOH.
GILLS: pale, pale pink(?)  , could be white. Shallow, crow0ded, branching and converging (there is a word for that.. please refresh my memory.)
STIPE: one cylindrical, the other tapering upward. Slight but abrupt bulbious base. Slightly irregular knob. Slight (<1/3 dia) hollow in top half of stipe.The stipe broke away from the cap and left the cottony PARTIAL VEIL attached to the margin. No sign of GILL ATTACHMENT on stipe.
AROMA: Mild, no phenol.
HABITAT: in soil under cypress near the ocean.
              ---------<<<*>>>------- Added Info.....
My wife swears that this is Agaricus hondensis.  I found some while driving north of Petaluma years ago.  We both handled them. She had a swollen face within a few hours (not rash/blistering like poison oak). I was fine.  She freaks out on hondensis and xanthodermis to this day. 

I think it's an A. hondensis too.  Gotta wash my hands and all utensils now...

description: This is another one of those Lactarius I find locally that has characteristics of both L. rufulus and L. rubidus. It's large and has orange hairs at the tip of its stipe and cream colored spores, but its stipe is hollow like L. rubidus (not just the pinhole hollow that is common in L. rufulus), and most strongly it smells like fresh rubidus. Also, relative to its larger size its substance seems more rubidus. Rufulus would feel chunkier, more dense, and heavier for its size. To me this seems 50/50 rufulus/rubidus.
